</div>I think we have sufficient proof to determine that she knew her chances to live would reduced by refusing the transfusion.  Unless I am mistaken, the JWs don't believe that adherence to biblical principles guarantees continuation of physical life.  So her death wasn't solely happenstance.  Or maybe a better way to say it would be that her will was involved in creating the circumstances surrounding her death.  <br />
<br />
So its fair to criticize her principles.  The question is one of relative value: is the principle of following one's own religious beliefs of higher value than the principle of being around for one's own children?  Both principles involve alot of faith - faith that god's will is being followed, faith that the children will end up fine, etc.  <br />
<br />
But it needn't all be faith.  And it shouldn't automatically be thought of as bad because the kids lost their mother.  She may have thought it through and, hell, even prepared the kids and other family members for this eventuality.  The family might admire her for standing by her beliefs and may be inspired to be better people as a result.  Its fairly rare to find someone with enough intestinal fortitude to stand by their own beliefs, right or wrong, to the point of death.  I'm not going to snap-judge someone willing to lay everything on the line like that.</div>
